  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law prohibits money laundering in most countries around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as if it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is illegal under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, which make it a federal crime to engage in financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nSimilarly, many other countries have their own anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. International cooperation is also facilitated through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nFailure to comply with AML laws can result in severe consequences for individuals, businesses, and financial institutions.",
